n and coronoid processes of the ulnar wrap around the trochlea of the humerus","The ulnar articulates with the carpal bones directly","The ulnar is the primary bone involved in wrist movement"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct statement is that the \u003Cstrong\u003Eolecranon and coronoid processes of the ulnar wrap around the trochlea of the humerus\u003C/strong\u003E. This articulation forms part of the elbow joint, allowing for flexion and extension of the forearm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe ulnar is shorter than the radius\u003C/strong\u003E - The ulnra is actually longer and extends more proximally at the elbow\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe ulnar finishes more distally than the radius\u003C/strong\u003E - The ulnar extends more proximally at the elbow, not distally\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe ulnar articulates with the carpal bones directly\u003C/strong\u003E - The ulnar does not directly articulate with the carpal bones; the radius does\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe ulnar is the primary bone involved in wrist movement\u003C/strong\u003E - The radius is primarily involved in wrist movement\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ulna is one of the two bones in the forearm, the other being the radius.","The olecranon and coronoid processes of the ulna form part of the elbow joint by articulating with the humerus.","The ulna is longer than the radius and extends more proximally at the elbow."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder 